INTRODUCTION¶

I am interested in looking at the Kickstarter dataset on Kaggle, to see if I can come up with indicators of what it takes to succeed in such platforms. From 2009 to 2020, there have been over 500'000 projects launched on this platform, and together they have pledged over 5.4 billion dollars from 20 million backers. (source: https://www.kickstarter.com/help/stats), but the success rate of projects is merely below 40%, and my question is if we can use the publicly available data from the stats of these projects to estimate the success rate of new projects, and potentially create a dashboard that can help set up a campaign that would have a higher potential for succeeding.

The 'failed' campaigns had pledged around 500MM that were not collected from backers - that's 25MM of unrealized profits for the Kickstarter platform, and a lot of heartbreak both for the creators and the backers of the failed projects - I'm excited to see if data science can save the day.

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY¶

The dataset needs a fair amount of clean up, but has a lot of useful information. So far, I have looked at the goal amount, campaign duration, country, category, and the name of projects to find potential correlation with the success rate, and also with amount pledged - in the basic studies that I have done, goal amount and country have little to do with success rate, duration of the campaign has minimal relation, but category and name of the project are definitely worth looking at. Right now my data does not have project descriptions in the data set, but since project IDs are present, that information might be available as well through scraping or combining other data sets.

After finding description, next steps are to create a NLP model to look at project titles and descriptions.

def convert_date(x):
    try:
        x = datetime.datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S').date()
    except:
        try:
            x = datetime.datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%d').date() 
        except:
            x = np.nan
    return x
